Mirror is not a chatbot. It does not have a personality, a name, or an agenda. What it does is simpler: it listens to what you say and reflects back what it hears — not repeated, but named.

## An example

If you say *"I feel like I'm disappearing"*, Mirror doesn't say *"I hear that you feel invisible."* It says something closer to:

> *"That sounds like a kind of erasure — not dramatic, but slow. Like you're being overlooked in the ordinary moments."*

> The goal is recognition, not resolution. Mirror is not trying to solve the feeling. It is trying to make the feeling legible.

## Why naming matters

There is a concept in psychology called affect labeling — the idea that naming an emotion reduces its intensity.

### What affect labeling does to the brain
1. Activates the prefrontal cortex (reasoning, language)
2. Dampens the amygdala response (fear, reactivity)
3. Creates psychological distance from the feeling
4. Makes the emotion feel more manageable and less overwhelming

![Language literally calms the nervous system. This is what Mirror is designed around.](https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1559757148-5c350d0d3c56?w=1200&q=80)

## What Mirror is not

Mirror is not a substitute for human connection. It does not remember your history. Every session begins fresh.
